Hey Nick,

Thanks for your response. These credentials are indeed the latter; just the`token` field in the rclone config. As for the naming convention, I'm a bit stumped myself as to what would be best to call it; Perhaps `--dropbox-token` would be more intuitive? Please let me know your thoughts.

With regards to "Would storing the credentials in a file be easier for people?"; I personally think that (outside of corporate environments) storing the creds in the config file as-is is just fine. It also feels quite intuitive.

I've gone ahead and created a [WIP branch](https://github.com/ncw/rclone/pull/2852). The gist of the changes are as follows: 

1.  The addition of the `--dropbox-token `flag in `backend/dropbox/dropbox.go`:
```
if opt.Token != "" {
		config.SetValue(name, config.ConfigToken, opt.Token)
	}
```
2. And the addition of a `SetValue` method in `fs/config/config.go`(as opposed to use of `SetValueAndSave`), such that only the runtime config is modified, rather than runtime config + the `rclone.conf` file.
```
// SetValue sets the key to the value and saves just that
// value in the RUNTIME config. No changes are writen
// back to the users on-disk config file.
func SetValue(name, key, value string) (err error) {
	// Set the value in the runtime config only
	getConfigData().SetValue(name, key, value)
	return nil
}
```

Please let me know your thoughts on the implementation. Everything builds and works great on my end (I tested with an rclone lsjson). This change was much smaller than I initially anticipated, but I'm not sure if these changes (particularly the additional `SetValue`) method are the correct way to do it.

Thank you

-Jake

@tgallant I don't think anyone is working on this at the moment.

What were you thinking of? I think just adding a "token" config value (advanced setting) should probably be enough to enable it. So another value like these?

```go
{
                        Name: config.ConfigClientID,
                        Help: "Google Application Client Id\nSetting your own is recommended.\nSee https://rclone.org/drive/#making-your-own-client-id for how to create your own.\nIf you leave this blank, it will use an internal key which is low performance.",
                }, {
                        Name: config.ConfigClientSecret,
                        Help: "Google Application Client Secret\nSetting your own is recommended.",
                }
```

Potentially these 3 settings could be factored out of all the oauth using backends...

thinking about this some more... how about this as an option for factoring:

in `oauthutil.go` define a `SharedOptions` data structure

```go
var SharedOptions = []fs.Option{{
	Name: config.ConfigClientID,
	Help: "OAuth Client Id\nLeave blank normally.",
}, {
	Name: config.ConfigClientSecret,
	Help: "OAuth Client Secret\nLeave blank normally.",
}, {
	Name: config.ConfigToken,
	Help: "OAuth Access Token as a JSON blob",
}, {
	Name:     config.ConfigAuthURL,
	Help:     "OAuth server URL.\nLeave blank normally.",
	Advanced: true,
}, {
	Name:     config.ConfigTokenURL,
	Help:     "Token server url.\nleave blank normally.",
	Advanced: true,
}}
```

then in the relevant backends define the Options like this

```go
fs.Register(&fs.RegInfo{
...

Options: append([]fs.Option{{
	Name:     "impersonate",
	Help:     "Impersonate this user when using a business account.",
	Default:  "",
	Advanced: true,
}, {
	Name:     "blah",
	Help:     "blah",
}}, oauthutil.SharedOptions...),

...
```
